  {
    "title": "The SI System and Base Units",
    "objective": "Define the SI system and identify the fundamental base units for length, mass, time, and temperature.",
    "retrievalTextLines": [
      "In the electrical industry, we use a universal language called SI Units, which stands for Système International. This ensures that a measurement taken in one country means exactly the same thing in another. Base units are the fundamental building blocks that are not derived from any other unit.",
      "For length, the base unit is the Metre (m). For mass, we use the Kilogram (kg). It is important to distinguish mass from weight; mass is the amount of matter in an object, whereas weight is a force. For time, the standard unit is the Second (s). For temperature, the official SI base unit is the Kelvin (K). While we use Celsius in daily life, Kelvin is the standard for scientific calculations to ensure consistency across all thermal equations."
    ],
    "hint": "Think of the four fundamental measurements: distance, matter, duration, and heat."
  },
  {
    "title": "Derived Units for Physical Quantities",
    "objective": "Identify derived SI units for area, volume, density, and velocity.",
    "retrievalTextLines": [
      "Derived units are created by mathematically combining base units together. For example, if you multiply a length by a width, you get Area, which is measured in square metres (m²). If you add a third dimension of depth, you get Volume, measured in cubic metres (m³). Electricians use these to calculate the cross-sectional area of cables or the internal space of containment like trunking.",
      "Velocity is another derived unit that measures how far something travels over a specific time, expressed as metres per second (m/s). Density describes how much mass is packed into a specific volume, measured in kilograms per cubic metre (kg/m³). Every derived unit is simply a combination of the original base units (m, kg, s) used to describe more complex physical properties."
    ],
    "hint": "Remember that these units are 'built' from base units like the metre and kilogram."
  },
  {
    "title": "Core Electrical Quantities",
    "objective": "Identify the SI units for current, voltage, resistance, and power.",
    "retrievalTextLines": [
      "Electrical science relies on four primary quantities that describe how electricity behaves in a circuit. Current is the flow of electrical charge, measured in Amperes (A), often shortened to 'Amps.' Voltage is the electrical potential difference, or the 'pressure' that pushes the current through a circuit, measured in Volts (V).",
      "Resistance is the opposition to that flow, measured in Ohms. The symbol for the Ohm is the Greek letter Omega (Ω). To help visualize this, think of voltage as the pump pressure in a water pipe and current as the water flow; resistance is a restriction in the pipe that slows the water down. Finally, Power is the rate at which electrical energy is converted into another form, such as heat or light, and is measured in Watts (W)."
    ],
    "hint": "Focus on the four pillars: flow (A), pressure (V), opposition (Ω), and rate of work (W)."
  },
  {
    "title": "Frequency, Energy, and Resistivity",
    "objective": "Determine the correct SI units for frequency, energy, and resistivity.",
    "retrievalTextLines": [
      "Beyond the basic four, we measure specific characteristics of electrical systems. Frequency describes how many complete cycles an alternating current (AC) makes in one second, measured in Hertz (Hz). Energy is the total amount of work done over a period of time. While Power (Watts) tells us how fast work is being done, Energy tells us the total amount used, measured in Joules (J).",
      "We also use Resistivity to describe how well a material conducts electricity. While Resistance (Ω) changes based on the length or thickness of a specific wire, Resistivity is a fixed property of the material itself (such as copper). It is measured in Ohm-metres (Ωm). This value allows electricians to calculate the resistance of any cable based on the material it is made from."
    ],
    "hint": "Distinguish between the 'rate' of work (Watts) and the 'total' work (Joules)."
  },
  {
    "title": "Reactance, Impedance, and Power Factor",
    "objective": "Identify units for complex electrical quantities including inductance, capacitance, and impedance.",
    "retrievalTextLines": [
      "In AC circuits, components like coils and capacitors create opposition to current flow through magnetic and electric fields. Inductance (L) is the property of a coil, measured in Henrys (H). Capacitance (C) is the ability to store charge, measured in Farads (F). Both of these create a type of opposition called Reactance, which is measured in Ohms (Ω).",
      "When we combine standard resistance with reactance, the total opposition in an AC circuit is called Impedance (Z), which is also measured in Ohms (Ω). Finally, we measure the efficiency of an AC circuit using the Power Factor. Because Power Factor is a ratio comparing two power values, it is a 'dimensionless' quantity, meaning it has no unit or symbol associated with it."
    ],
    "hint": "Recall that any form of 'opposition' to current, whether resistance, reactance, or impedance, uses the Ohm (Ω)."
  }
]

